{{Infobox person | name = Alain Gheerbrant | image = File:Alain026.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1920|12|27|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Paris]], [[France]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2013|2|21|1920|12|27|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Paris]], [[France]]<ref name=DAG>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livreshebdo.fr/article/deces-dalain-gheerbrant-editeur-ethnologue-et-ecrivain |title=Décès d'Alain Gheerbrant, éditeur, ethnologue et écrivain |website=livreshebdo.fr |date=2013-02-21 |accessdate=2018-02-05 |language=fr }}</ref> | residence = | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = [[Lycée Saint-Jean-de-Passy]] | occupation = Writer, poet, editor, explorer | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | home_town = | television = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | children = | awards = | signature = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | footnotes = }}
'''Alain Gheerbrant''' (27 December 1920 – 21 February 2013) was a French writer, editor, poet and explorer, noted for his expedition inside the [[Amazon basin|basins]] of Amazonian rivers.<ref name=DAG />
== Career == Alain Gheerbrant was the first [[avant-garde]] publisher, founder of the publishing house K Éditeur,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gheerbrant |first1=Alain |last2=Aichelbaum |first2=Léon |date=1991 |title=K éditeur |url= |language=fr |location=Cognac |publisher=[[Le Temps qu'il fait]] |isbn=9782868531094}}</ref> which published in particular the works by [[Antonin Artaud]], [[Benjamin Péret]], [[Georges Bataille]], [[Aimé Césaire]], et cetera. For the second edition of ''[[Story of the Eye]]'' by Bataille, Gheerbrant introduced Bataille to the German artist [[Hans Bellmer]] in May 1946: "It was tempting, says Gheerbrant, to make a dialogue between a [[papist]] and a [[Lutheran]] on their common obsession. One's Nordic and surgical precision was made to give shape to the nocturnal and romantic imaginations of the other. The project took their common approval from the outset."<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gheerbrant |first1=Alain |last2=Aichelbaum |first2=Léon |date=1991 |title=K éditeur |series=Coll. « La Part du Livre » |page=18 |url= |language=fr |location=Cognac |publisher=Le Temps qu'il fait |isbn=9782868531094}}</ref> Moreover, the book has been entirely rewritten by Bataille himself, still published by K Éditeur.
From 1948 to 1950, Alain Gheerbrant led the [[Orinoco]]-[[Amazon River|Amazon]] expedition. He travelled through the basin of both rivers for two years and wrote of his travels in {{lang|fr|L'Expédition Orénoque-Amazone|italic=yes}} (1952). He is considered the first Westerner who had peaceful contact with the [[Yanomami Indians]] and also the first to cross the [[Parima Mountains]] between 1948 and 1950. In 1952, he directed a documentary film called {{lang|fr|Des hommes qu'on appelle sauvages|italic=yes}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9059185/ |title=Alain Gheerbrant, Director |website=[[imdb.com]] |accessdate=2018-02-05 }}</ref>
He has produced numerous reports all over the world and published {{lang|fr|Dictionnaire des symboles}} in 1982, a collaborative work with [[Jean Chevalier]], an encyclopaedia of cultural anthropology about the symbolism of myths and folklore, which was republished 19 times between 1982 and 1997. He has authored an illustrated [[Pocket edition|pocket book]] for the "[[Découvertes Gallimard]]" [[Collection (publishing)|collection]], called {{lang|fr|L'Amazone, un géant blessé|italic=yes}} (1988), which has been translated into eleven languages, including English. In 1995, he released his memoir entitled {{lang|fr|La Transversale}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/236065/alain-gheerbrant |title=Alain Gheerbrant |website=[[Penguin Random House]] |accessdate=2018-02-05 }}</ref>
== Selected Bibliography == * ''L'expédition Orénoque-Amazone (1948–1950)'', « Hors série Connaissance ». Éditions Gallimard, 1952 * ''Congo noir et blanc'', « Hors série Connaissance ». Éditions Gallimard, 1956 * ''The Incas'', Orion Press, 1961 * ''Journey to the Far Amazon: An Expedition Into Unknown Territory'', Simon & Schuster, 1964 * ''The Rebel Church in Latin America'', Penguin Books, 1974 * Collab. with [[Jean Chevalier]], ''Dictionnaire des symboles'', Éditions Robert Laffont, 1982 ** ''Dictionary of Symbols'', Penguin Books, 1996 * ''L'Amazone, un géant blessé'', collection « [[Découvertes Gallimard]] » (nº 40), série Histoire. Éditions Gallimard, 1988 (new edition in 2005)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gallimard.fr/Catalogue/GALLIMARD/Decouvertes-Gallimard/Decouvertes-Gallimard/Histoire/L-Amazone-un-geant-blesse |title=''L'Amazone, un géant blessé'', collection Découvertes Gallimard (n° 40) |publisher=[[Éditions Gallimard]] |accessdate=2018-02-05 |language=fr}}</ref> ** US edition – ''The Amazon: Past, Present, and Future'', "[[Abrams Discoveries]]" series. Harry N. Abrams, 1992 ** UK edition – ''The Amazon: Past, Present and Future'', '[[New Horizons (Thames & Hudson)|New Horizons]]' series. Thames & Hudson, 1992 * ''La Transversale'', Actes Sud, 1998
