{{Infobox language |name=Early New High German |nativename=''Deutsch'' |region=[[Germany]], parts of [[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]] |era=[[Late Middle Ages]], [[Early modern period]] |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Germanic languages|Germanic]] |fam3=[[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] |fam4=[[German language|German]] |ancestor=[[Old High German]] |ancestor2=[[Middle High German]] |isoexception=historical |glotto=none |notice=IPA }}
'''Early New High German''' ('''ENHG''') is a term for the period in the history of the [[German language]], generally defined, following [[Wilhelm Scherer]],{{sfn|Scherer|1878|p=13}} as the period 1350 to 1650.{{sfn|Wells|1987|p=23|ps=. "1350–1650... seems the most widely accepted dating."}}
The term is the standard translation of the German {{lang|de|Frühneuhochdeutsch}} (Fnhd., Frnhd.), introduced by Scherer. The term ''Early Modern High German'' is also occasionally used for this period (but the abbreviation EMHG is generally used for ''[[Middle High German|Early Middle High German]]'').
==Periodisation== [[File:Luther 1534, Genesis I.jpg|thumb|The opening page of the Book of Genesis in Martin Luther's Bible translation of 1534, published by Hans Luft]] The start and end dates of ENHG are, like all linguistic [[periodisation]]s, somewhat arbitrary. In spite of many alternative suggestions, Scherer's dates still command widespread acceptance.{{sfn|Roelke|1998|ps=. lists the various suggestions.}} Linguistically, the mid 14th-century is marked by the phonological changes to the [[vowel|vowel system]] that characterise the modern standard language; the mid 17th sees the loss of status for regional forms of language, and the triumph of German over [[Latin]] as the dominant, and then sole, language for public discourse.
Scherer's dates also have the merit of coinciding with two major demographic catastrophes with linguistic consequences: the [[Black Death]], and the end of the [[Thirty Years' War]]. Arguably, the [[Peace of Westphalia]] in 1648, by ending religious wars and creating a Germany of many small sovereign states, brought about the essential political conditions for the final development of a universally acceptable standard language in the subsequent [[New High German]] period.
Alternative periodisations take the period to begin later, such as the invention of [[movable type|printing with moveable type]] in the 1450s.{{sfn|Wells|1987|p=25}}
==Geographical variation== There was no standard Early New High German, and all forms of language display some local or regional characteristics. However, there was increasing harmonisation in the written and printed word, the start of developments towards the unified standard which was [[Codification (linguistics)|codified]] in the New High German period. ===The Dialects=== With the end of [[Ostsiedlung|eastward expansion]], the geographical spread and the [[dialect]] map of German in the ENHG period remained the same as at the close of the MHG period.{{sfn|Schmidt|2013|page=349}} {| class="wikitable" cellpadding=5 style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;" |- !ENHG Dialects{{sfn|Schmidt|2013|page=349}}{{sfn|Piirainen|1985|page=1371}} !West !East |- ! [[Central German]] | [[Ripuarian language|Ripuarian]]
[[Moselle Franconian dialects|Moselle Franconian]]
[[Rhine Franconian dialects|Rhine Franconian]]
