==={{lang|de|Druckersprachen}}, "printers' languages"=== [[File:Printer in 1568-ce.png|thumb| A printing press, {{circa|1568}}]] Since the printers had a commercial interest in making their texts acceptable to a wide readership, they often strove to avoid purely local forms of language.{{sfn|Bach|1965|page=254}} This gave rise to so-called {{lang|de|Druckersprachen}} ("printers' languages"), which are not necessarily identical to the spoken dialect of the town where the press was located.{{sfn|Schmidt|2013|page=349}} The most important centres of printing, with their regional {{lang|de|Druckersprachen}} are: *'''[[West Central German]]''': [[Frankfurt]], [[Mainz]], [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], [[Cologne]] *'''[[East Central German]]''': [[Wittenberg]], [[Erfurt]], [[Leipzig]] *'''[[Swabian German|Swabian]]''': [[Augsburg]], [[Ulm]], [[Tübingen]] *'''[[Alemannic German|Alemannic]]''': [[Basel]], [[Strassburg]], [[Zürich]] *'''[[East Franconian German|East Franconian]]''': [[Nuremberg]], [[Bamberg]], [[Würzburg]] *'''[[Bavarian dialects|Austro-Bavarian]]''': [[Ingolstadt]], [[Vienna]].{{sfn|Schmidt|2013|page=350}}
===Chancery Languages=== While the language of the printers remained regional, the period saw the gradual development of two forms of German (one Upper German, one Central German), which were supra-regional: the {{lang|de|Schriftsprachen}} ("written languages", "documentary languages") of the [[Chancery (medieval office)|chanceries]] of the two main political centres. {{sfn|Keller|1978|pages=365–368}} * The {{lang|gmh|gemaine tiutsch}} ("common German") of the [[Chancery (medieval office)|Chancery]] of the [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Maximilian I]] and his successors in [[Prague]] and then Vienna. * The [[East Central German]] of the Chancery of the [[Electorate of Saxony]] in [[Meissen]] The language of these centres had influence well beyond their own territorial and dialect boundaries.
The influence of the Saxon Chancery was due in part to its adoption for his own published works by Martin Luther, who stated, "{{lang|de|Ich rede nach der sächsischen Canzley, welcher nachfolgen alle Fürsten und Könige in Deutschland}}" ("My language is based on that of the Saxon Chancery, which is followed by all the princes and kings in Germany").{{sfn|Luther|1566|loc=1040}}
He also recognized the standardising force of the two chanceries: "{{lang|de|Kaiser Maximilian und Kurf. Friedrich, H. zu Sachsen etc. haben im römischen Reich die deutschen Sprachen also in eine gewisse Sprache gezogen}}" ("The Emperor Maximilian and [[Frederick III, Elector of Saxony|Duke Frederick, Elector of Saxony etc.]], have drawn the languages of Germany together").{{sfn|Luther|1566|loc=1040}}
===Low German=== [[Middle Low German]], spoken across the whole of [[Northern Germany]] north of the [[Benrath Line]] in the [[Middle Ages]], was a distinct [[West Germanic]] language. From the start of the 16th century, however, High German came increasingly to be used in this area not only in writing, but also in the pulpit and in schools. By the end of the ENHG period Low German had almost completely ceased to be used in writing or in formal and public speech, and had become the low status variant in a [[diglossia|diglossic]] situation, with High German as the high status variant.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegera|2005|p=34}}
==Phonology and orthography== For a number of reasons it is not possible to give a single phonological system for ENHG: * dialectal variation * the differing times at which individual dialects introduced even shared sound changes * the lack of a prestige variant (such as the "Dichtersprache" provides for [[Middle High German]]) Also, the difficulty of deriving phonological information from the complexity of ENHG orthography means that many reference works do not treat orthography and phonology separately for this period.{{sfn|Ebert|Reichmann|Solms|Wegera|1993|pages=13–17|ps=, has detailed discussion of the issues.|loc=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LcUiAAAAQBAJ]}}
===Vowels=== The MHG vowel system undergoes significant changes in the transition to ENHG and their uneven geographical distribution has served to further differentiate the modern dialects.
====Diphthongisation==== [[File:ENHG diphthongisation.jpg|thumb|The diphthongisation of long vowels in ENHG]] The long high vowels {{IPA|/iː/}}, {{IPA|/uː/}} and {{IPA|/yː/}} (spelt {{angle bracket|î}}, {{angle bracket|û}} and {{angle bracket|iu}}) are [[diphthong]]ised to {{IPA|/aɪ/}}, {{IPA|/aʊ/}} and {{IPA|/ɔʏ/}}. spelt {{angle bracket|ei}}, {{angle bracket|au}} and {{angle bracket|eu/äu}}. They thus fall together with the original MHG diphthongs {{angle bracket|ei}}, {{angle bracket|ou}} and {{angle bracket|öu}} {{IPA|/øy/}}, which are all lowered.
Examples: *MHG ''snîden'' ("to cut") > NHG ''schneiden'' *MHG ''hût'' ("skin") > NHG ''Haut'' *MHG ''liute'' ("people") > NHG ''Leute''.
This change started as early as the 12th century in Upper Bavarian and only reached Moselle Franconian in the 16th century. It does not affect Alemannic or Ripuarian dialects, which still retain the original long vowels. The map shows the distribution and chronology of this sound change.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegara|2005|pp=134–136}}
====Monophthongisation==== The MHG falling diphthongs {{IPA|/iə/}}, {{IPA|/uə/}} and {{IPA|/yə/}} (spelt {{angle bracket|ie}}, {{angle bracket|uo}} and {{angle bracket|üe}}) are [[monophthong]]ised, replacing the long high vowels lost in the diphthongisation. In the case of {{IPA|/iə/}} > {{IPA|/iː/}} the MHG spelling is retained and in Modern German {{angle bracket|ie}} indicates the long vowel.
Examples: *MHG ''liebe'' ("love) > NHG ''Liebe'' {{IPA|/liːbə/}} *MHG ''bruoder'' ("brother") > NHG ''Bruder'' {{IPA|/bruːdər/}} *MHG ''brüeder'' ("brothers") > NHG ''Brüder'' {{IPA|/bryːdər/}}
This change, sometimes called the Central German Monophthongisation, affects mainly the Central German dialects, along with South Franconian and East Franconian. The other Upper German dialects largely retain the original diphthongs.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegara|2005|pp=136}}{{sfn|Wolf|1985|p=1310}}
====Changes in Vowel Quantity==== There are two changes in vowel quantity in ENHG, the lengthening of short vowels and the shortening of long vowel. Both show wide variation between dialects, but appear earlier and more completely in Central German dialects. Many individual words form exceptions to these changes, though the lengthening is carried out more consistently.{{sfn|von Kienle|1969|p=37}}{{sfn|Waterman|1966|p=103}}{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegera|2005|p=137}}
'''1. Lengthening''': MHG short vowels in open syllables (that is, syllables which end in a vowel) tend to be lengthened in the ENHG period. This is not reflected directly in spelling, but it is the source of the Modern German spelling convention that a vowel ending a syllable is always long.{{sfn|von Kienle|1969|pp=37–40}}
Examples: *MHG ''sagen'' {{IPA|/zagən/}} ("to say") > NHG ''sagen'' {{IPA|/zaːgən/}} *MHG ''übel'' {{IPA|/ybəl/}} ("evil") > NHG ''Übel'' {{IPA|/yːbəl/}}
'''2. Shortening''': MHG long vowels tend to be shortened in the ENHG period before certain consonants ({{IPA|m}}, {{IPA|t}} and others) and before certainconsonant combinations ({{IPA|/xt/}}, {{IPA|/ft/}}, and {{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/r/}} followed by another consonant).{{sfn|von Kienle|1969|pp=40–42}}
Examples: *MHG ''hât'' ("has") > NHG ''hat'' *MHG ''dâhte'' ("thought") > NHG ''dachte'' *MHG ''lêrche'' ("lark") > NHG ''Lerche'' *MHG ''jâmer'' ("suffering") > NHG ''Jammer'' This shortening seems to have taken place later than the monophthongisation, since the long vowels which result from that change are often shortened.
Examples: *MHG ''muoter'' ("mother" > NHG ''Mutter'' (via {{IPA|/muːtər/}}) *MHG ''lieht'' ("light" > NHG ''Licht'' (via {{IPA|/liːxt/}})
===Consonants=== The overall consonant system of German remains largely unchanged in the transition from MHG to Modern German. However, in many cases sounds changed in particular environments and therefore changed in distribution.{{sfn|Wolf|1985|p=1310}} Some of the more significant are the following. (In addition there are many other changes in particular dialects or in particular words.) ====/s/==== #MHG had two sibilants, written {{angle bracket|s}}/{{angle bracket|ss}} and {{angle bracket|z}}/{{angle bracket|zz}}. The difference between these is uncertain, but in ENHG both fell together in /s/. (The affricate {{IPA|/t͡s/}}, for which {{angle bracket|z}} is also used, remained unchanged.) #Before vowels this {{IPA|/s/}} becomes voiced to {{IPA|/z/}}, e.g. MHG ''sehen'' {{IPA|/sehən/}} ("to see") > NHG ''sehen'' {{IPA|/zeːən/}}. #Initially before consonants {{IPA|/s/}} becomes {{IPA|/ʃ/}}, indicated by the grapheme <sch>, e.g. MHG ''snîden'' ("to cut") > NHG ''schneiden'' . Before /p/ and /t/ this is not indicated in spelling, e.g. MHG ''stein'' ("stone") > NHG ''Stein'' {{IPA|/ʃtain/}}.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegara|2005|pp=145–6}}
====/w/==== #In initial position the blibalial fricative {{IPA|/w/}} becomes the labio-dental {{IPA|/v/}}, though this is not reflected in any change in spelling, e.g. MHG ''wil'' ("want to") > NHG ''will'' {{IPA|/vil/}}. In a few words, this also takes place between vowels, e.g. ''ewig'' {{IPA|/eːvig/}} ("eternal"). #Otherwise it is either lost, e.g. MHG ''snėwes'' ("of the snow") > NHG ''Schnees'', or forms a diphthong with a neighbouring vowel (e.g. MHG ''brâwe'' ("brow") > NHG ''Braue''.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegara|2005|pp=146–7}}
====/h/==== #Medial /h/ is lost, though it remains in spelling to indicate the length of the preceding vowel, e.g. MHG ''sehen'' {{IPA|/sehən/}} ("to see") > NHG ''sehen'' {{IPA|/zeːən/}}.{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegara|2005|pp=147}}
The loss of {{IPA|/w/}} and the {{angle bracket|s}}:{{angle bracket|z}} contrast are the only structural changes to the consonant system.
==Morphology== As with phonology, the range of variation between dialects and time periods makes it impossible to cite a unified morphology for ENHG. The sound changes of the vowels had which brought consequent changes to * [[verb conjugation]]s * further simplification of the [[noun]] declensions
==Syntax== The following are the main syntactical developments in ENHG:{{sfn|Hartweg|Wegera|2005|pp=173–178}}{{sfn|Wells|1987|pp=227–262}}{{sfn|Keller|1978|pp=434–442}} *'''The Noun Phrase''' **'''Increasing complexity''': in chancery documents noun phrases increasingly incorporate prepositional and participial phases, and this development spreads from there to other types of formal and official writing. **'''Attributive genitive''': the so-called "[[English possessive|Saxon genitive]]", in which the genitive phrase precedes the noun (e.g. ''der sunnen schein'', literally "of-the-sun shine") increasingly makes way for the now standard post-nominal construction (e.g. ''der schein der sonne'', literally "the shine of the sun"), though it remains the norm where the noun in the genitive is a proper noun (''Marias Auto''). *'''The Verb Phrase''' **'''Increasing complexity''': more complex verbal constructions with participles and infinitives. **'''Verb position''': the positioning of verbal components characteristic of NHG (finite verb second in main clauses, first in subordinate clauses; non-finite verb forms in clause-final position) gradually becomes firmly established. **'''Decline of the preterite''': an earlier development in the spoken language (especially in Upper German), the replacement of simple preterite forms by perfect forms with an auxiliary verb and the past participle becomes increasingly common from the 17th century. **'''Negation''': double negation ceases to be acceptable as an intensified negation; the enclitic negative particle ''ne/en'' falls out of use and an adverb of negation (''nicht'', ''nie'') becomes obligatory (e.g.MHG ''ine weiz (niht)'', ENHG ''ich weiss nicht'', "I don't know"). *'''Case government''' **'''Decline of the genitive''': Verbs which take a genitive object increasingly replace this with an accusative object or a prepositional phrase. Prepositions which govern the genitive likewise tend to switch to the accusative.
==Literature== {{main|Early Modern German literature}} The period saw the invention of [[printing]] with moveable type (c.1455) and the [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]] (from 1517). Both of these were significant contributors to the development of the Modern German Standard language, as they further promoted the development of non-local forms of language and exposed all speakers to forms of German from outside their own area &mdash; even the illiterate, who were read ''to''. The most important single text of the period was [[Martin Luther|Luther]]'s [[Luther Bible|Bible translation]], the first part of which was published in 1522, though this is now not credited with the central role in creating the standard that was once attributed to it. This is also the first period in which [[prose]] works, both literary and discursive, became more numerous and more important than [[poetry|verse]].
==Example texts== ===The [[Gospel of John]], 1:1–5=== {| cellpadding=5 |- ! ! Luther, 1545{{sfn|Luther|1545|ps=. Printed in Wittenberg 1545; dialect East Central German}} ! Luther Bible, 2017{{sfn|Luther|2017}} ! King James Version |- valign=top | 1 | Im anfang war das Wort / Vnd das Wort war bey Gott / vnd Gott war das Wort. | Im Anfang war das Wort, und das Wort war bei Gott, und Gott war das Wort. | In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God. |- valign=top |2 | Das selbige war im anfang bey Gott. | Dasselbe war im Anfang bei Gott. | The same was in the beginning with God. |- valign=top |3 | Alle ding sind durch dasselbige gemacht / vnd on dasselbige ist nichts gemacht / was gemacht ist. | Alle Dinge sind durch dasselbe gemacht, und ohne dasselbe ist nichts gemacht, was gemacht ist. | All things were made by him; and without him was not any thing made that was made. |- valign=top |4 | Jn jm war das Leben / vnd das Leben war das Liecht der Menschen / | In ihm war das Leben, und das Leben war das Licht der Menschen. | In him was life; and the life was the light of men. |- valign=top |5 | vnd das Liecht scheinet in der Finsternis / vnd die Finsternis habens nicht begriffen. | Und das Licht scheint in der Finsternis, und die Finsternis hat's nicht ergriffen. | And the light shineth in darkness; and the darkness comprehended it not. |- valign=top |6 |ES ward ein Mensch von Gott gesand / der hies Johannes. |Es war ein Mensch, von Gott gesandt, der hieß Johannes. |There was a man sent from God, whose name was John. |- valign=top |7 |Derselbige kam zum zeugnis / das er von dem Liecht zeugete / auff das sie alle durch jn gleubten. |Der kam zum Zeugnis, damit er von dem Licht zeuge, auf dass alle durch ihn glaubten. |The same came for a witness, to bear witness of the Light, that all men through him might believe. |- valign=top |8 |Er war nicht das Liecht / sondern das er zeugete von dem Liecht. |Er war nicht das Licht, sondern er sollte zeugen von dem Licht. |He was not that Light, but was sent to bear witness of that Light. |- valign=top |9 |Das war das warhafftige Liecht / welchs alle Menschen erleuchtet / die in diese Welt komen. |Das war das wahre Licht, das alle Menschen erleuchtet, die in diese Welt kommen. |That was the true Light, which lighteth every man that cometh into the world. |}
===From ''[[Fortunatus (book)|Fortunatus]]''=== {| cellpadding=10 |- !Original{{sfn|Anonymous|1509|ps=. Printed in Augsburg; dialect Swabian}} !English translation{{sfn|Haldane|2005}} |- valign=top |Ain land, genanntt Cipern, Ist ain inßel vnd künigreich gegen der sonnen auffgang im mör gelegen, fast wunsam, lustig vnd fruchtbar aller handen edler natürlicher früchten, manigem wissend, der tzu dem hailigen land Jerusalem gefarn vnd im selben künigreich Cipern zugelendt vnd da gewesen ist. |The Kingdom of Cyprus is an island situated close to where the sun rises from the sea: a delightful, merry, fertile island, full of all kinds of fruits, and known to many who have landed and passed some time there on their journey to Jerusalem, in the Holy Land. |- valign=top |Darinn ain treffenliche statt, genannt Famagosta, in wölicher stat ain edler purger altz herkommens was geseßsen. |It contains a splendid city, Famagusta, which was once the seat of a noble burgher of ancient lineage. |- valign=top |Dem sein öltern groß hab vnnd gut verlassen hetten, allso, das er fast reich, mächtig vnnd darbey iung was, aines freyen muttes. |His parents had left him much money and property, so that he was very rich and powerful; but he was also very young and of a careless disposition. |- valign=top |Wenig betrachtet, wie seine elteren zu tzeiten das ir erspart vnd gemeert hettend, vnnd sein gemüt was gentzlichen gericht auff zeitlich eer, freüd vnd wollust des leibs. |He had taken but little notice of how his parents had saved and increased their money, and his mind was wholly preoccupied with the pursuit of honour and physical pleasures. |- |Vnd nam an sich ainen kostlichen stand mitt stechenn, turnieren, dem künig gen hoff tzureytten vnnd ander sachenn, Darmitt er groß gut on ward vnnd seine freünd wol kunden mercken, das er mer on ward, dann sein nutzung ertragen mocht, vnd gedachtend jm ain weib zu geben, ob sy jn von sollichem ziehen möchten, vnd legten ym das für. |So he maintained himself in great state, jousting, tourneying and travelling around with the King’s Court, and losing much money thereby. His friends, soon noticing that he was in danger of losing more than his means could bear, thought of giving him a wife, in the hope that she would curb his expenditure. When they suggested this to him, he was highly pleased, and he promised to follow their advice; and so they began to search for a suitable spouse. |}
