{{Infobox language |name=Mal |nativename=Thin |states=[[Laos]], [[Thailand]] |ethnicity= |speakers={{sigfig|26,200|2}} |date=1982 – 1995 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Khmuic languages|Khmuic]] |fam3=Mal–Phrai |iso3=mlf |glotto=mall1246 |glottorefname=Mal }}
'''Mal''', also known as '''Thin''', is a [[Mon–Khmer language]] of Laos and Thailand. It is one of several closely related languages which go by the names ''Thin'' or ''Prai''.
'''Tayten''' (300 speakers as of 1995) is spoken in the 2 villages of Ban Phia and Ban Tenngiou in Pakxeng District, Luang Prabang Province, Laos. It is either Thin or [[Tai Thanh language|Tai Then]].<ref>http://asiaharvest.org/wp-content/themes/asia/docs/people-groups/Laos/Tayten.jpg</ref>
